  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Last year my score for CAT was around 40 percentile. What should I do to score > 90  percentile this year?",
  "response": "Improving from a 40 percentile to a 90 percentile score in the Common Admission Test (CAT) is a significant leap and requires a structured approach. Here are some strategies to help you achieve this goal:\n\n### 1. Understand the Exam Format\n- **Familiarize Yourself with the Structure**: Make sure you understand the sections (Quantitative Ability, Data Interpretation & Logical Reasoning, and Verbal Ability & Reading Comprehension) and the types of questions asked.\n- **Review Previous Year Papers**: Look at past years' question papers to get an idea of patterns and frequently tested concepts.\n\n### 2. Assess Your Current Level\n- **Identify Strengths and Weaknesses**: Take a diagnostic test or mock exam to determine your current level and identify which sections you need to focus on more.\n- **Analyze Performance**: Understand where you lost marks\u2014was it a lack of knowledge, time management, or careless mistakes?\n\n### 3. Create a Study Plan\n- **Structured Study Schedule**: Make a realistic timeline that allocates dedicated time for each section based on your strengths and weaknesses.\n- **Balance Topics**: Ensure that you're covering fundamentals as well as advanced topics, particularly in Quantitative Ability.\n\n### 4. Build Strong Fundamentals\n- **Conceptual Clarity**: Focus on building strong concepts, especially in mathematics and verbal reasoning. Use good reference books and online resources.\n- **Practice Regularly**: Consistent practice is key. Aim for daily problem-solving sessions, emphasizing quality over quantity.\n\n### 5. Utilize Study Materials\n- **Coaching or Online Courses**: Consider enrolling in a coaching program if possible, as they can provide structured guidance and resources.\n- **Books & Resources**: Use well-recommended CAT preparation books and online platforms. Solve a variety of problems from each section.\n\n### 6. Practice Mock Tests\n- **Regular Mock Tests**: Take full-length mock tests periodically (weekly or bi-weekly) to build stamina and get used to the test format.\n- **Simulate Exam Conditions**: Practice these tests under timed conditions to help improve your time management skills.\n\n### 7. Analyze Mock Test Results\n- **Review Mistakes**: After each mock test, review what went wrong. Find out which types of questions you struggled with and work on those.\n- **Track Progress**: Keep a record of your scores and improvement over time.\n\n### 8. Time Management\n- **Work on Speed and Accuracy**: Develop strategies to solve questions faster without compromising accuracy.\n- **Avoid Overthinking**: Practice making quick decisions on easier questions to save time for more challenging ones.\n\n### 9. Focus on the Verbal Section\n- **Reading Comprehension**: Read newspapers and novels to improve comprehension skills. Practice summarizing articles to enhance understanding.\n- **Vocabulary**: Regularly study and practice vocabulary to help with verbal ability questions.\n\n### 10. Maintain Health and Well-being\n- **Stay Healthy**: Ensure you get enough rest, eat well, and manage stress effectively. A healthy mind and body can significantly improve performance.\n- **Balance Study and Rest**: Don't overburden yourself; include breaks and leisure activities in your study schedule.\n\n### 11. Join Study Groups\n- **Peer Learning**: Join a group or find study partners to discuss strategies and solve problems together. Teaching others can also reinforce your understanding.\n\n### 12. Stay Motivated\n- **Set Small Goals**: Break your larger goal into smaller, manageable milestones and celebrate achievements.\n- **Stay Positive**: Keep a positive mindset; believe in your capabilities and persistence will pay off.\n\nImproving your score significantly will require commitment and a focused approach, but with dedicated effort, you can achieve your goal of scoring above 90 percentile in CAT. Good luck!",
